    using Revise, PlutoUI, CoordinateTransformations, StaticArrays, Rotations, Viznet, Compose
    
    function viz_lattice(lt::Viznet.AbstractSites; ncolor, r)
        line_style=bondstyle(:default, stroke("#333333"), linewidth(4*unit(lt)*mm))
        colors = if ncolor==1
            ["#333333"]
        elseif ncolor==2
            ["#CC4040", "#4040CC"]
        elseif ncolor==3
            ["#CC4040", "#40CC40", "#4040CC"]
        else
            error("!!")
        end
        node_styles = [nodestyle(:circle, fill(color), r=r) for color in colors]
        #text_style=textstyle(:default, fontsize(unit(lt)*100pt)), labels=vertices(lt)
        canvas() do
            for (i,node) in enumerate(Viznet.vertices(lt))
                rand(node_styles) &gt;&gt; lt[node]
                #text_style &gt;&gt; (lt[node], "$(labels[i])")
            end
            for bond in Viznet.bonds(lt)
                line_style &gt;&gt; lt[bond[1]; bond[2]]
            end
        end
    end
    
    
    function _spring_layout(adj_matrix::AbstractMatrix,
                           locs_x=2*rand(size(adj_matrix, 1)).-1.0,
                           locs_y=2*rand(size(adj_matrix, 1)).-1.0;
                           C=2.0,
                           MAXITER=100,
                           INITTEMP=2.0)

        nvg = size(adj_matrix, 1)

        # The optimal distance bewteen vertices
        k = C * sqrt(4.0 / nvg)
        kÂ² = k * k

        # Store forces and apply at end of iteration all at once
        force_x = zeros(nvg)
        force_y = zeros(nvg)

        # Iterate MAXITER times
        @inbounds for iter = 1:MAXITER
            # Calculate forces
            for i = 1:nvg
                force_vec_x = 0.0
                force_vec_y = 0.0
                for j = 1:nvg
                    i == j && continue
                    d_x = locs_x[j] - locs_x[i]
                    d_y = locs_y[j] - locs_y[i]
                    distÂ²  = (d_x * d_x) + (d_y * d_y)
                    dist = sqrt(distÂ²)

                    if !( iszero(adj_matrix[i,j]) && iszero(adj_matrix[j,i]) )
                        # Attractive + repulsive force
                        # F_d = distÂ² / k - kÂ² / dist # original FR algorithm
                        F_d = dist / k - kÂ² / distÂ²
                    else
                        # Just repulsive
                        # F_d = -kÂ² / dist  # original FR algorithm
                        F_d = -kÂ² / distÂ²
                    end
                    force_vec_x += F_d*d_x
                    force_vec_y += F_d*d_y
                end
                force_x[i] = force_vec_x
                force_y[i] = force_vec_y
            end
            # Cool down
            temp = INITTEMP / iter
            # Now apply them, but limit to temperature
            for i = 1:nvg
                fx = force_x[i]
                fy = force_y[i]
                force_mag  = sqrt((fx * fx) + (fy * fy))
                scale      = min(force_mag, temp) / force_mag
                locs_x[i] += force_x[i] * scale
                locs_y[i] += force_y[i] * scale
            end
        end

        # Scale to unit square
        min_x, max_x = minimum(locs_x), maximum(locs_x)
        min_y, max_y = minimum(locs_y), maximum(locs_y)
        function scaler(z, a, b)
            2.0*((z - a)/(b - a)) - 1.0
        end
        map!(z -&gt; scaler(z, min_x, max_x), locs_x, locs_x)
        map!(z -&gt; scaler(z, min_y, max_y), locs_y, locs_y)

        return [((x+1)/2, (y+1)/2) for (x, y) in zip(locs_x, locs_y)]
    end

    function viz_graph(graph; r=0.25/sqrt(nv(graph)+1), show_edgeindex=false,
        node_fontsize=100pt/sqrt(nv(graph)+1),
        edge_fontsize=200pt/sqrt(nv(graph)+1),
        labels=1:nv(graph),
        locs=_spring_layout(adjacency_matrix(graph)),
        linecolor="#333333",
        node_edgecolor="transparent",
        node_facecolors=["#CC4040", "#4040CC"]
    )
        nt = nv(graph)
        nbs = [nodestyle(:default, fill(c), stroke(node_edgecolor), linewidth(2mm/sqrt(nv(graph)+1)); r=r) for c in node_facecolors]
        eb = bondstyle(:default, linewidth(3mm/sqrt(nv(graph)+1)), stroke(linecolor))
        Compose.compose(Compose.context(r, r, 1-2r, 1-2r), canvas() do
            for (loc, label) in zip(locs, labels)
                rand(nbs) &gt;&gt; loc
            end
            for edge in edges(graph)
                eb &gt;&gt; (locs[edge.src], locs[edge.dst])
            end
        end)
    end

    struct Cubic{T}

<script>const getParentCell = el => el.closest("pluto-cell")

const getHeaders = () => {
	const depth = Math.max(1, Math.min(6, 3)) // should be in range 1:6
	const range = Array.from({length: depth}, (x, i) => i+1) // [1, ..., depth]
	
	const selector = range.map(i => `pluto-notebook pluto-cell h${i}`).join(",")
	return Array.from(document.querySelectorAll(selector))
}

const indent = true
const aside = true

const clickHandler = (event) => {
	const path = (event.path || event.composedPath())
	const toc = path.find(elem => elem?.classList?.contains?.("toc-toggle"))
	if (toc) {
		event.stopImmediatePropagation()
		toc.closest(".plutoui-toc").classList.toggle("hide")
	}
}

document.addEventListener("click", clickHandler)


const render = (el) => html`${el.map(h => {
	const parent_cell = getParentCell(h)

	const a = html`<a 
		class="${h.nodeName}" 
		href="#${parent_cell.id}"
	>${h.innerText}</a>`
	/* a.onmouseover=()=>{
		parent_cell.firstElementChild.classList.add(
			'highlight-pluto-cell-shoulder'
		)
	}
	a.onmouseout=() => {
		parent_cell.firstElementChild.classList.remove(
			'highlight-pluto-cell-shoulder'
		)
	} */
	a.onclick=(e) => {
		e.preventDefault();
		h.scrollIntoView({
			behavior: 'smooth', 
			block: 'start'
		})
	}

	return html`<div class="toc-row">${a}</div>`
})}`

const tocNode = html`<nav class="plutoui-toc">
	<header>
     <span class="toc-toggle open-toc">ðŸ“–</span>
     <span class="toc-toggle closed-toc">ðŸ“•</span>
	Table of Contents</header>
	<section></section>
</nav>`

tocNode.classList.toggle("aside", aside)
tocNode.classList.toggle("indent", indent)

const updateCallback = () => {
	tocNode.querySelector("section").replaceWith(
		html`<section>${render(getHeaders())}</section>`
	)
}
updateCallback()
setTimeout(updateCallback, 100)
setTimeout(updateCallback, 1000)
setTimeout(updateCallback, 5000)

const notebook = document.querySelector("pluto-notebook")


// We have a mutationobserver for each cell:
const observers = {
	current: [],
}

const createCellObservers = () => {
	observers.current.forEach((o) => o.disconnect())
	observers.current = Array.from(notebook.querySelectorAll("pluto-cell")).map(el => {
		const o = new MutationObserver(updateCallback)
		o.observe(el, {attributeFilter: ["class"]})
		return o
	})
}
createCellObservers()

// And one for the notebook's child list, which updates our cell observers:
const notebookObserver = new MutationObserver(() => {
	updateCallback()
	createCellObservers()
})
notebookObserver.observe(notebook, {childList: true})

// And finally, an observer for the document.body classList, to make sure that the toc also works when if is loaded during notebook initialization
const bodyClassObserver = new MutationObserver(updateCallback)
bodyClassObserver.observe(document.body, {attributeFilter: ["class"]})

// Hide/show the ToC when the screen gets small
let m = matchMedia("(max-width: 1000px)")
let match_listener = () => 
	tocNode.classList.toggle("hide", m.matches)
match_listener()
m.addListener(match_listener)

invalidation.then(() => {
	notebookObserver.disconnect()
	bodyClassObserver.disconnect()
	observers.current.forEach((o) => o.disconnect())
	document.removeEventListener("click", clickHandler)
	m.removeListener(match_listener)
})

return tocNode
</script><style>@media not print {

<div class="markdown"><h2>What is a tropical tensor network?</h2>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>A Tropical tensor network is a tensor network with Tropical numbers inside.</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p><strong>What is a tensor network?</strong></p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Tensor network is a generalization of matrix multiplication to multiple tensors. The graphical representation of matrix multiplication is</p>
<p class="tex">$$Y&#91;i,j&#93; :&#61; \sum_k A&#91;i,k&#93; \times B&#91;k,j&#93;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let

    tb2 = textstyle(:default, fontsize(40px), fill("white"))
    y0 = 0.15
    x = (0.3, y0)
    y = (0.7, y0)
    img = canvas() do
        sq &gt;&gt; x
        sq &gt;&gt; y
        eb &gt;&gt; (x, y)
        eb &gt;&gt; (x, (0.0, y0))
        eb &gt;&gt; (x, (1.0, y0))
        tb &gt;&gt; ((0.1, y0+0.05), "i")
        tb &gt;&gt; ((0.9, y0+0.05), "j")
        tb &gt;&gt; ((0.5, y0+0.05), "k")
        tb2 &gt;&gt; (x, "A")
        tb2 &gt;&gt; (y, "B")
    end
    Compose.compose(context(0.38, 0.0, 1/1.5^2, 2.0), img)
end

<div class="markdown"><ul>
<li><p>a matrix is a tensor of rank-2, it is represented as a vertex with two labeled edges &#40;or legs&#41;,</p>
</li>
<li><p>the <strong>contraction</strong> &#40;a generalization of matrix multiplication to tensors&#41; is represented by connecting legs with same labels, where connecting a pair of legs means <strong>sum-product</strong> over a specific degree of freedom corresponding to the leg label,</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>We replace matrices with tensors, matrix multiplication with tensor contraction and allow more than two nodes in the graph, and we will get a tensor network. The following is an example of graphical representation of a tensor network</p>
<p class="tex">$$Y&#91;n&#93; :&#61; \sum_&#123;i,j,k,l,m&#125; A&#91;i,l&#93; \times B&#91;i,j&#93; \times C&#91;j,k,n&#93; \times D&#91;k,l,m&#93; \times E&#91;m&#93;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(14cm, 7cm)
    sq = nodestyle(:square; r=0.07)
    wb = nodestyle(:square, fill("white"); r=0.04)
    eb = bondstyle(:line)
    tb = textstyle(:default, fontsize(25px))
    tb2 = textstyle(:default, fontsize(30px), fill("white"))
    x0 = 0.15
    x1 = 0.65
    y0 = 0.35
    y1 = 0.8
    x3 = 0.9
    y3 = 0.1
    a = (x0, y0)
    b = (x0, y1)
    c = (x1, y1)
    d = (x1, y0)
    e = (x3, y3)
    img = canvas() do
        for (loc, label) in [(a, "A"), (b, "B"), (c, "C"), (d, "D"), (e, "E")]
            sq &gt;&gt; loc
            tb2 &gt;&gt; (loc, label)
        end
        for (edge, label) in [((a, b), "i"), ((b, c), "j"), ((c, d), "k"), ((a, d), "l"), ((d,e), "m"), ((c, (0.9, 0.55)), "n")]
            eb &gt;&gt; edge
            wb &gt;&gt; ((edge[1] .+ edge[2]) ./ 2)
            tb &gt;&gt; ((edge[1] .+ edge[2]) ./ 2, label)
        end
    end
    Compose.compose(context(.38, 0, .5, 1), img)
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><ul>
<li><p>A tensor of rank <span class="tex">$n$</span> is represented as a vertex with <span class="tex">$n$</span> labeled legs,</p>
</li>
<li><p>A tensor network is represented as an <strong>open simple graph</strong>. It is a representation of the contraction of multiple tensors, the output is a tensor of rank-&#40;the number of unpaired legs&#41;</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p><em>To know more about tensor networks:</em></p>
<ul>
<li><p><a href="https://tensornetwork.org/">Tensor network website</a></p>
</li>
<li><p>A Practical Introduction to Tensor Networks: Matrix Product States and Projected Entangled Pair States, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1306.2164">arXiv: 1306.2164</a></p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p><strong>What are tropical numbers?</strong></p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Tropical numbers are numbers with tropical algebra. Tropical algebra is defined by replacing the usual sum and product operators for ordinary real numbers with the max and sum operators respectively </p>
<p class="tex">$$\begin&#123;align&#125;
&amp;a âŠ• b &#61; \max&#40;a, b&#41;\\
&amp;a âŠ™ b &#61; a &#43; b
\end&#123;align&#125;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>Tropical(3.0) * Tropical(2.0)</code></pre>
<pre id='var-hash125830' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>5.0â‚œ</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>Tropical(3.0) + Tropical(2.0)</code></pre>
<pre id='var-hash149794' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>3.0â‚œ</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p><strong>Tropical algebra is a semi-ring&#33;</strong></p>
<p>The <span class="tex">$\oplus$</span> and <span class="tex">$\odot$</span> operators still have commutative, associative, and distributive properties. However, since there is no additive inverse, the <span class="tex">$\oplus$</span> and <span class="tex">$\odot$</span> and operations define a semiring over <span class="tex">$\mathbb R \cup \&#123;-\infty\&#125;$</span>. </p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>One sees that <span class="tex">$-\infty$</span> acts as zero element for the tropical number since  <span class="tex">$-\infty \oplus x &#61; x  &#36; and &#36;-\infty \odot x &#61; -\infty$</span>. </p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'># Float64 is the storage type of Tropical number
zero(Tropical{Float64})</code></pre>
<pre id='var-hash330943' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>-Infâ‚œ</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>On the other hand, <span class="tex">$0$</span> acts as the multiplicative identity since <span class="tex">$0 \odot x &#61; x$</span></p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>one(Tropical{Float64})</code></pre>
<pre id='var-hash172350' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>0.0â‚œ</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p><strong>Tropical matrix multiplication</strong></p>
<p>By putting tropical numbers inside matrices, we get tropical matrix multiplication.</p>
<p class="tex">$$\begin&#123;align&#125;
\cancel&#123;Y&#91;i,j&#93; :&#61; \sum_k A&#91;i,k&#93; \times B&#91;k,j&#93;&#125;\\

Y&#91;i,j&#93; :&#61; \max_k &#40;A&#91;i,k&#93; &#43; B&#91;k,j&#93;&#41;
\end&#123;align&#125;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(15cm, 10/3*cm)
    sq = nodestyle(:circle; r=0.1)
    eb = bondstyle(:line)
    tb = textstyle(:default, fontsize(25px))
    tb2 = textstyle(:default, fontsize(40px), fill("white"))
    y0 = 0.15
    x = (0.3, y0)
    y = (0.7, y0)
    img = canvas() do
        sq &gt;&gt; x
        sq &gt;&gt; y
        eb &gt;&gt; (x, y)
        eb &gt;&gt; (x, (0.0, y0))
        eb &gt;&gt; (x, (1.0, y0))
        tb &gt;&gt; ((0.1, y0+0.05), "i")
        tb &gt;&gt; ((0.9, y0+0.05), "j")
        tb &gt;&gt; ((0.5, y0+0.05), "k")
        tb2 &gt;&gt; (x, "A")
        tb2 &gt;&gt; (y, "B")
    end
    Compose.compose(context(0.38, 0.0, 1/1.5^2, 2.0), img)
end

<div class="markdown"><p>Tropical matrix multiplication is directly related to finding the shortest path. Consider the following graph</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(14cm, 7cm)
    sq = nodestyle(:circle, fill("white"), stroke("black"); r=0.08)
    wb = nodestyle(:circle, fill("white"); r=0.05)
    eb = bondstyle(:line, stroke("black"), linewidth(0.5mm))
    tb = textstyle(:default, fontsize(25px))
    x0 = 0.15
    x1 = 0.65
    y0 = 0.35
    y1 = 0.8
    x3 = 0.9
    y3 = 0.1
    a = (x0, y0)
    b = (x0, y1)
    c = (x1, y1)
    d = (x1, y0)
    e = (x3, y3)
    nodes = [a, b, c, d, e]
    img = canvas() do
        for (loc, label) in zip(nodes, ["A", "B", "C", "D", "E"])
            sq &gt;&gt; loc
            tb &gt;&gt; (loc, label)
        end
        for edge in [(1,2), (2,3), (3,4), (1,4), (4,5), (1,3)]
            x, y, = nodes[edge[1]],nodes[edge[2]]
            eb &gt;&gt; (x, y)
            wb &gt;&gt; ((x .+ y) ./ 2)
            tb &gt;&gt; ((x .+ y) ./ 2, string(-Int(neg_adjmatrix[edge...].n)))
        end
    end
    Compose.compose(context(.38, 0, .5, 1), img)
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><p>What is the shorted parth from <code>B</code> to <code>E</code>?</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>First, represent the negative adjacency matrix <span class="tex">$-A$</span> with tropical matrix.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'># we broadcast the `Tropical` function to each element of the adjacency matrix
neg_adjmatrix = Tropical.(-[Inf 5 3 2 Inf;
        5 Inf 7 Inf Inf;
        3 7 Inf 2 Inf;
        2 Inf 2 Inf 3;
        Inf Inf Inf 3 Inf])</code></pre>
<pre id='var-neg_adjmatrix' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>5Ã—5 Matrix{TropicalF64}:
 -Infâ‚œ  -5.0â‚œ  -3.0â‚œ  -2.0â‚œ  -Infâ‚œ
 -5.0â‚œ  -Infâ‚œ  -7.0â‚œ  -Infâ‚œ  -Infâ‚œ
 -3.0â‚œ  -7.0â‚œ  -Infâ‚œ  -2.0â‚œ  -Infâ‚œ
 -2.0â‚œ  -Infâ‚œ  -2.0â‚œ  -Infâ‚œ  -3.0â‚œ
 -Infâ‚œ  -Infâ‚œ  -Infâ‚œ  -3.0â‚œ  -Infâ‚œ</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>The power of <span class="tex">$-A$</span> is</p>
<p class="tex">$$&#40;&#40;-A&#41;^m&#41;_&#123;i_1i_m&#125; :&#61; \max_&#123;i_1,i_2,\ldots i_m&#125; \left&#40;&#40;-A&#41;_&#123;i_1i_2&#125; &#43; &#40;-A&#41;_&#123;i_2i_3&#125; &#43;\ldots &#40;-A&#41;_&#123;i_&#123;m-1&#125;i_m&#125;\right&#41;$$</p>
<p>Then the shortest path between <span class="tex">$i_1$</span> and <span class="tex">$i_m$</span> can be represented as</p>
<p class="tex">$$-\max&#40;&#40;-A&#41;_&#123;i_1i_m&#125;, &#40;-A&#41;^2_&#123;i_1i_m&#125;, \ldots &#40;-A&#41;^n_&#123;i_1i_m&#125;&#41;$$</p>
<p>where <span class="tex">$n$</span> is the number of vertices. The power stops at order <span class="tex">$n$</span> because it shortest path contains at most <span class="tex">$n$</span> edges.</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Hence, the shortest path between <code>B</code> and <code>E</code> is</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'># the `Tropical{Float64}` has only one field `n` of type `Float64`
# `2` and `5` are for indexing `B` and `E`
-maximum([(neg_adjmatrix^n)[2,5].n for n=1:5])</code></pre>
<pre id='var-hash151037' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>10.0</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p><em>To know more about applications of tropical matrices</em></p>
<ul>
<li><p><a href="https://personalpages.manchester.ac.uk/staff/mark.muldoon/Teaching/DiscreteMaths/LectureNotes/TropicalShortestPaths.pdf">Tropical Arithmetic and Shortest Paths</a></p>
</li>
<li><p><a href="https://link.springer.com/chapter/10.1007/BFb0023465">Methods and Applications of &#40;max,&#43;&#41; Linear Algebra</a></p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p><strong>Tropical tensor networks</strong></p>
<p>By putting Tropical numbers inside tensor networks, we get</p>
<p class="tex">$$\begin&#123;align&#125;
\cancel&#123;Y&#91;n&#93; :&#61; \sum_&#123;i,j,k,l,m&#125; A&#91;i,l&#93; \times B&#91;i,j&#93; \times C&#91;j,k,n&#93; \times D&#91;k,l,m&#93; \times E&#91;m&#93;&#125;\\

Y&#91;n&#93; :&#61; \max_&#123;i,j,k,l,m&#125; &#40;A&#91;i,l&#93; &#43; B&#91;i,j&#93; &#43; C&#91;j,k,n&#93; &#43; D&#91;k,l,m&#93; &#43; E&#91;m&#93;&#41;
\end&#123;align&#125;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(14cm, 7cm)
    sq = nodestyle(:circle; r=0.085)
    wb = nodestyle(:circle, fill("white"); r=0.04)
    eb = bondstyle(:line)
    tb = textstyle(:default, fontsize(25px))
    tb2 = textstyle(:default, fontsize(30px), fill("white"))
    x0 = 0.15
    x1 = 0.65
    y0 = 0.35
    y1 = 0.8
    x3 = 0.9
    y3 = 0.1
    a = (x0, y0)
    b = (x0, y1)
    c = (x1, y1)
    d = (x1, y0)
    e = (x3, y3)
    img = canvas() do
        for (loc, label) in [(a, "A"), (b, "B"), (c, "C"), (d, "D"), (e, "E")]
            sq &gt;&gt; loc
            tb2 &gt;&gt; (loc, label)
        end
        for (edge, label) in [((a, b), "i"), ((b, c), "j"), ((c, d), "k"), ((a, d), "l"), ((d,e), "m"), ((c, (0.9, 0.55)), "n")]
            eb &gt;&gt; edge
            wb &gt;&gt; ((edge[1] .+ edge[2]) ./ 2)
            tb &gt;&gt; ((edge[1] .+ edge[2]) ./ 2, label)
        end
    end
    Compose.compose(context(.38, 0, .5, 1), img)
end

<div class="markdown"><h3>Ising Spin glass</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>decision: NP-Complete</p>
</li>
<li><p>counting: #P-complete</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Ising spin glass is an energy model defined on a graph. It is about finding the maximum of the following energy function</p>
<p class="tex">$$-E &#61; \sum\limits_&#123;i,j\in E&#125; J_&#123;ij&#125; s_i s_j &#43; \sum\limits_&#123;i\in V&#125; h_&#123;i&#125; s_i$$</p>
<p>where <span class="tex">$s_i,s_j,\ldots s_n \in \&#123;-1,1\&#125;$</span>, this problem is hard because there are <span class="tex">$2^n$</span> possible configurations of <span class="tex">$\&#123;s_1,s_2\ldots s_n\&#125;$</span>. We define <span class="tex">$-E$</span> rather than <span class="tex">$E$</span> directly because people are more interested to know the ground state &#40;state with the lowest energy&#41; rather than the highest energy. The decision version of Ising spin glass is NP-complete, which mean it is unlikely to find a solution to the problem <em>&quot;what is the lowest possible energy?&quot;</em> in polynomial time on a classical computer. Its counting version asks <em>&quot;what is the number of possible configurations that gives the lowest energy&quot;</em>. It is #P-complete, which is at least as difficult as its dicision version.</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Let&#39;s take <span class="tex">$h_i&#61;0$</span> from now on, it will not change the complexity of the problem.</p>
</div>

    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(14cm, 7cm)
    sq = nodestyle(:circle, fill("white"), stroke("black"); r=0.08)
    wb = nodestyle(:circle, fill("white"); r=0.05)
    eb = bondstyle(:line, stroke("red"), linewidth(0.5mm))
    eb_ = bondstyle(:line, stroke("blue"), linewidth(0.5mm))
    tb = textstyle(:default, fontsize(25px), font("times"))
    tb2 = textstyle(:default, fontsize(30px), fill("black"), font("times"))
    x0 = 0.15
    x1 = 0.65
    y0 = 0.35
    y1 = 0.8
    x3 = 0.9
    y3 = 0.1
    a = (x0, y0)
    b = (x0, y1)
    c = (x1, y1)
    d = (x1, y0)
    e = (x3, y3)
    img = canvas() do
        for (loc, label) in [(a, "sâ‚"), (b, "sâ‚‚"), (c, "sâ‚ƒ"), (d, "sâ‚„"), (e, "sâ‚…")]
            sq &gt;&gt; loc
            tb2 &gt;&gt; (loc, label)
        end
        for (edge, J, label) in [((a, b), J12, "Jâ‚â‚‚"), ((b, c), J23, "Jâ‚‚â‚ƒ"), ((c, d), J34, "Jâ‚ƒâ‚„"), ((a, d), J14, "Jâ‚â‚„"), ((d,e), J45, "Jâ‚„â‚…"), ((c, a), J13, "Jâ‚â‚ƒ")]
            (J &gt; 0 ? eb : eb_) &gt;&gt; edge
            wb &gt;&gt; ((edge[1] .+ edge[2]) ./ 2)
            tb &gt;&gt; ((edge[1] .+ edge[2]) ./ 2, label)
        end
    end
    Compose.compose(context(.38, 0, .5, 1), img)
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><p>The goal is to find an optimal assignment of <span class="tex">$s_1, s_2,\ldots s_n$</span> that minimizes the energy. Mapping the problem to Einsum is straight-forward. We can rewrite the energy definition in tropical contraction format</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p class="tex">$$\begin&#123;align&#125;
-E &#61; &amp;\max_&#123;s_1,s_2,s_3,s_4, s_5&#125;
T_e&#40;J_&#123;12&#125;&#41;_&#123;s_1s_2&#125;&#43;
T_e&#40;J_&#123;23&#125;&#41;_&#123;s_2s_3&#125;&#43;
T_e&#40;J_&#123;34&#125;&#41;_&#123;s_3s_4&#125;&#43;\\
&amp;T_e&#40;J_&#123;14&#125;&#41;_&#123;s_1s_4&#125;&#43;
T_e&#40;J_&#123;45&#125;&#41;_&#123;s_4s_5&#125;&#43;
T_e&#40;J_&#123;13&#125;&#41;_&#123;s_1s_3&#125;
\end&#123;align&#125;$$</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>where edge tensors are defined as</p>
<p class="tex">$$T_&#123;e&#125;&#40;J_&#123;ij&#125;&#41;_&#123;s_i s_j&#125; &#61; \begin&#123;bmatrix&#125;J_&#123;ij&#125; &amp; -J_&#123;ij&#125; \\-J_&#123;ij&#125; &amp; J_&#123;ij&#125;\end&#123;bmatrix&#125;_&#123;s_is_j&#125;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function ising_bondtensor(::Type{T}, J) where T
    e = T(J)
    e_ = T(-J)
    [e e_; e_ e]
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-ising_bondtensor' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>ising_bondtensor (generic function with 1 method)</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>where a spin <span class="tex">$s_i &#61; 1$</span> &#40;or <span class="tex">$s_i&#61;-1$</span>&#41; is equivalent to <span class="tex">$1$</span> &#40;or <span class="tex">$2$</span>&#41; when used in matrix indexing. One can easily check it is the same as the previous negative energy function. We can also add a magnetic field at each vertex by placing a tensor <span class="tex">$T_v$</span> of rank-1 at each vertex.</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p class="tex">$$T_&#123;v&#125; &#61; \begin&#123;bmatrix&#125;
 h\\
 -h
\end&#123;bmatrix&#125;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function ising_vertextensor(::Type{T}, h) where T
    T[h, -h]
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-ising_vertextensor' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>ising_vertextensor (generic function with 1 method)</pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>html"""&lt;p&gt;The graphical representation is as follows, where small circles and big circles are for vertex tensors and edge tensors respectively.&lt;/p&gt;"""</code></pre>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(14cm, 7cm)
    sq = nodestyle(:circle, fill("black"); r=0.02)
    wb = nodestyle(:circle, fill("black"); r=0.06)
    eb = bondstyle(:line)
    tb = textstyle(:default, fontsize(20px), fill("white"))
    tb2 = textstyle(:default, fontsize(20px), fill("black"), font("times"))
    #tb3 = textstyle(:default, fontsize(15px), fill("green"))
    x0 = 0.15
    x1 = 0.65
    y0 = 0.35
    y1 = 0.8
    x3 = 0.9
    y3 = 0.1
    a = (x0, y0)
    b = (x0, y1)
    c = (x1, y1)
    d = (x1, y0)
    e = (x3, y3)
    img = canvas() do
        for (loc, label) in [(a, "â†‘"), (b, "â†“"), (c, "â†‘"), (d, "â†‘"), (e, "â†“")]
            sq &gt;&gt; loc
            #tb2 &gt;&gt; (loc, label)
        end
        for (edge, label) in [((a, b), "+1"), ((b, c), "-1"), ((c, d), "-1"), ((a, d), "+1"), ((d,e), "+1"), ((c, a), "+1")]
            eb &gt;&gt; edge
            wb &gt;&gt; ((edge[1] .+ edge[2]) ./ 2)
            tb &gt;&gt; ((edge[1] .+ edge[2]) ./ 2, label == "+1" ? "Tâ‚‘" : "Tâ‚‘'")
        end
        for lt in [((0.08, 0.3),"Táµ¥"), ((0.08,0.75), "Táµ¥"), ((0.75, 0.35),"Táµ¥"), ((0.75,0.8), "Táµ¥"), ((0.97,0.1), "Táµ¥")]
            tb2 &gt;&gt; lt
        end
        #for (i,edge) in enumerate([(a, b), (b, c), (c, d), (a, d), (d,e), (c, a)])
        #	tb3 &gt;&gt; (edge[1] .* 0.2 .+ edge[2] .* 0.8, "($i, T)")
        #	tb3 &gt;&gt; (edge[1] .* 0.8 .+ edge[2] .* 0.2, "($i, F)")
        #end
    end
    Compose.compose(context(.38, 0, .5, 1), img)

<div class="markdown"><p>This is a generalized tensor network that indices <span class="tex">$s_&#123;1&#125;, s_3$</span> and <span class="tex">$s_&#123;4&#125;$</span> appears more than twice and inner degree of freedom <span class="tex">$s_5$</span> appears only once, while all indices appears once for open legs or and twice for inner degree of freedoms in a tensor network. This generalized tensor network can be represented as an <code>einsum</code> notation.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'># we use the `@ein_str` macro from OMEinsum to perform the contraction
# Here we use a, b, c, d, e to represent the original vertex labels 1, 2, 3, 4, 5
ein"ab,bc,cd,ad,de,ac,a,b,c,d,e-&gt;"([ising_bondtensor(Tropical{Float64}, J) for J in [J12, J23, J34, J14, J45, J13]]..., fill(ising_vertextensor(Tropical{Float64}, 0.0), 5)...)[]</code></pre>
<pre id='var-hash984697' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>4.0â‚œ</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>In the <code>einsum</code> contraction notation, we use &quot;<code>-&gt;</code>&quot; to seperate inputs and output &#40;empty for scalar output&#41;, &quot;<code>,</code>&quot; to seperate different inputs. This notation is consistent with <a href="https://ajcr.net/Basic-guide-to-einsum/">the one in numpy</a>. Its contraction order is not optimized by default, one needs to call the <code>optimize_code</code> function in <a href="https://github.com/TensorBFS/OMEinsumContractionOrders.jl">OMEinsumContractionOrders</a> to get a tensor network with optimized order.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>using OMEinsumContractionOrders</code></pre>


<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>optimized_tnet = let
    code = ein"ab,bc,cd,ad,de,ac,a,b,c,d,e-&gt;"
    optimize_code(code, uniformsize(code, 2), TreeSA())
end</code></pre>

â”‚     â”œâ”€ ca, cd -> ad

â”‚     â”‚  â””â”€ ca, ca -> ca

â”‚     â”‚     â”‚  â‹®

<div class="markdown"><p>The tensor network is then contracted with the greedy algorithm.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>contraction_result = optimized_tnet([ising_bondtensor(Tropical{Float64}, J) for J in [J12, J23, J34, J14, J45, J13]]..., fill(ising_vertextensor(Tropical{Float64}, 0.0), 5)...)[]</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><p>The mininum energy is -4.</p>

<div class="markdown"><h5>Using Tropical numbers for counting</h5>
<p>Moreover, one can also employ the present approach to count the number of ground states at the same computational complexity of computing the ground state energy. To implement this, we further generalize the tensor element to be a tuple <span class="tex">$&#40;n, c&#41;$</span> composed by a tropical number <span class="tex">$x$</span> and an ordinary number <span class="tex">$n$</span>. The tropical number records the negative energy, while the ordinary number counts the number of minimal energy configurations. For tensor network contraction, we need the multiplication and addition of the tuple: <span class="tex">$&#40;n_1, c_1&#41; \odot &#40;n_2,c_2&#41; &#61; &#40;n_1 &#43; n_2, c_1\cdot c_2&#41;$</span> and </p>
<p class="tex">$$\begin&#123;equation&#125;
    &#40;n_1, c_1&#41;\oplus &#40;n_2, c_2&#41; &#61; \begin&#123;cases&#125;
 &#40;n_1\oplus n_2, \, c_1 &#43; c_2 &#41; &amp; \text&#123;if &#36;n_1 &#61; n_2&#36;&#125; \\
 &#40;n_1\oplus n_2,\, c_1 &#41; &amp; \text&#123;if &#36;n_1&gt;n_2&#36;&#125; \\
 &#40;n_1\oplus n_2,\, c_2 &#41;&amp; \text&#123;if &#36;n_1 &lt; n_2&#36;&#125;
 \end&#123;cases&#125;.
\end&#123;equation&#125;$$</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>It corresponds to the following four processes of concatenating and comparing configrations on graphs &#40;or tensor networks&#41;.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(15cm, 10cm)
    a = 0.1
    b = 0.05
    nodes = [(-a, -b), (a, -b), (a, b), (-a, b)]
    nb = Compose.compose(context(), polygon(nodes), stroke("black"), fill("white"))
    tb = textstyle(:default)
    tt = Compose.compose(context(), text(0.0, 0.0, ""))
    x_title = 0.1
    canvas() do
        for (y_1, op, title) in zip(
                [0.2, 0.4, 0.6, 0.8],
                ["âŠ™", "âŠ•", "âŠ•", "âŠ•"],
                [
                ("concatenate best configurations of two subgraphs", "value = nâ‚\ndegeneracy = câ‚", "value = nâ‚‚\ndegeneracy = câ‚‚", "value = nâ‚ + nâ‚‚\ndegeneracy = câ‚ * câ‚‚"),
                ("compare two configurations: case nâ‚ == nâ‚‚", "value = n\ndegeneracy = câ‚", "value = n\ndegeneracy = câ‚‚", "value = n\ndegeneracy = câ‚ + câ‚‚"),
                ("compare two configurations: case nâ‚ &gt; nâ‚‚", "value = nâ‚\ndegeneracy = câ‚", "value = nâ‚‚\ndegeneracy = câ‚‚", "value = nâ‚ \ndegeneracy = câ‚"),
                ("compare two configurations: case nâ‚ &lt; nâ‚‚", "value = nâ‚\ndegeneracy = câ‚", "value = nâ‚‚\ndegeneracy = câ‚‚", "value = nâ‚‚\ndegeneracy = câ‚‚")
                ]
            )
            x = (0.2, y_1)
            y = (0.5, y_1)
            z = (0.8, y_1)
            nb &gt;&gt; x
            nb &gt;&gt; y
            nb &gt;&gt; z
            tt &gt;&gt; ((x_title, y_1-0.08), title[1])
            tb &gt;&gt; (x, title[2])
            tb &gt;&gt; (y, title[3])
            tb &gt;&gt; ((x .+ y) ./ 2, op)
            tb &gt;&gt; ((z .+ y) ./ 2, "=")
            tb &gt;&gt; (z, title[4])
        end
    end
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><h3>Max 2-satisfiability problem</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>decision: NP-complete</p>
</li>
<li><p>counting: #P-complete</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>A 2-satisfiability problem may be described using a Boolean expression with a special restricted form. It is a conjunction &#40;a Boolean and operation&#41; of clauses, where each clause is a disjunction &#40;a Boolean or operation&#41; of two variables or negated variables. The following is an example of 2-SAT problem of size <span class="tex">$6$</span></p>
<p class="tex">$$\begin&#123;align&#125;
&amp; &#40;x_&#123;0&#125;\lor x_&#123;2&#125;&#41;\land &#40;x_&#123;0&#125;\lor \lnot x_&#123;3&#125;&#41;\land &#40;x_&#123;1&#125;\lor \lnot x_&#123;3&#125;&#41;\land &#40;x_&#123;1&#125;\lor \lnot x_&#123;4&#125;&#41;\land \\
&amp; &#40;x_&#123;2&#125;\lor \lnot x_&#123;4&#125;&#41;\land &#123;&#125;&#40;x_&#123;0&#125;\lor \lnot x_&#123;5&#125;&#41;\land &#40;x_&#123;1&#125;\lor \lnot x_&#123;5&#125;&#41;\land &#40;x_&#123;2&#125;\lor \lnot x_&#123;5&#125;&#41;\land \\
&amp;&#40;x_&#123;3&#125;\lor x_&#123;6&#125;&#41;\land &#40;x_&#123;4&#125;\lor x_&#123;6&#125;&#41;\land &#40;x_&#123;5&#125;\lor x_&#123;6&#125;&#41;.
\end&#123;align&#125;$$</p>
<p>&#40;from <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2-satisfiability">wiki</a>&#41;</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>We define an energy function</p>
<p class="tex">$$E &#61; \sum\limits_&#123;k&#61;1&#125;^&#123;|C|&#125; C_k&#40;s_&#123;i_k&#125;, s_&#123;j_k&#125;&#41;$$</p>
<p>where <span class="tex">$C_k&#40;s_&#123;i_k&#125;, s_&#123;j_k&#125;&#41;$</span> is <span class="tex">$&#43;1$</span> if the <span class="tex">$k$</span>th clause on <span class="tex">$i$</span>th and <span class="tex">$j$</span>th boolean variable is satisfied, otherwise, it is <span class="tex">$-1$</span>. In the tensor network representation, we use <span class="tex">$s_&#123;i_k&#125; \in \&#123;0, 1\&#125;$</span> to denote the degree of freedom associated with variable <span class="tex">$i_k$</span>.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function twosat_vertextensor(::Type{T}, n::Int) where T
    res = zeros(T, fill(2, n)...)
    res[1] = one(T)
    res[end] = one(T)
    return res
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-twosat_vertextensor' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>twosat_vertextensor (generic function with 1 method)</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>If two vertices are related by a clause <span class="tex">$C_k$</span>, we add an bond tensor <span class="tex">$T_k$</span> to connect two vertices.</p>
<p class="tex">$$&#40;T_&#123;k&#125;&#41;_&#123;s_i s_j&#125; &#61; C_k&#40;s_i,s_j&#41;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function twosat_bondtensor(::Type{T}, src::Bool, dst::Bool) where T
    res = [T(1) T(1); T(1) T(1)]
    res[Int(src)+1, Int(dst)+1] = T(-1)
    return res
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-twosat_bondtensor' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>twosat_bondtensor (generic function with 1 method)</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>The degeneracy can also be obtained easily with <code>einsum</code> &#40;without using vertex tensors&#41;</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    T = CountingTropical{Float64}
    ein"ac,ad,bd,be,ce,af,bf,cf,dg,eg,fg-&gt;"(
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, true),
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, false),
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, false),
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, false),
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, false),
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, false),
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, false),
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, false),
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, true),
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, true),
        twosat_bondtensor(T, true, true),
    )[]
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-hash112020' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>(11.0, 16.0)â‚œ</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>Since the resulting &#40;counting&#41; tropical number 11 is equal to the number of clauses, all clauses are satisfied, and the degeneracy is 16. &#40;Note: this contraction is not computational efficient, for large scale problem, one should use the contraction order algorithms listed in Sec. 5.&#41;</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h3>Potts model</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>decision: NP-Complete</p>
</li>
<li><p>counting: #P-complete</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>The Potts model is generalization of Ising model, where a spin takes one of <span class="tex">$q$</span> possible values, distributed uniformly about the circle, at angles <span class="tex">$\theta _&#123;n&#125;&#61;&#123;\frac  &#123;2\pi n&#125;&#123;q&#125;&#125;$</span>, where <span class="tex">$n &#61; 0, 1, ..., q-1$</span> and that the interaction Hamiltonian be given by</p>
<p class="tex">$$H&#61;J\sum _&#123;&#123;i,j \in E&#125;&#125;\cos \left&#40;\theta _&#123;&#123;s_&#123;i&#125;&#125;&#125;-\theta _&#123;&#123;s_&#123;j&#125;&#125;&#125;\right&#41;$$</p>
<p>For <span class="tex">$q&#61;3$</span>, we have the edge tensor</p>
<p class="tex">$$T_e &#61; J\begin&#123;bmatrix&#125;1 &amp; -1/2 &amp; -1/2 \\ -1/2 &amp; 1 &amp; -1/2 \\ -1/2 &amp; -1/2 &amp; 1\end&#123;bmatrix&#125;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function potts_bondtensor(::Type{T}, ::Val{q}, J) where {T, q}
    angles = cos.(2Ï€ .* ((1:q) ./ q))
    res = zeros(T, q, q)
    for i=1:q
        for j=1:q
            res[i,j] = T(J*angles[mod1(abs(j-i), q)])
        end
    end
    res
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-potts_bondtensor' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>potts_bondtensor (generic function with 1 method)</pre>


<div class="markdown"><h3>Maximum independent set</h3>
<ul>
<li><p>hardness: NP-Complete</p>
</li>
<li><p>counting: #P-complete</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>A maximal independent set &#40;MIS&#41; is an independent set that is not a subset of any other independent set. Let&#39;s still use this graph as an example.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(14cm, 7cm)
    sq = nodestyle(:circle, fill("white"), stroke("black"); r=0.08)
    wb = nodestyle(:circle, fill("white"); r=0.05)
    eb = bondstyle(:line, stroke("black"), linewidth(0.5mm))
    tb = textstyle(:default, fontsize(25px), font("times"))
    tb2 = textstyle(:default, fontsize(30px), fill("black"), font("times"))
    x0 = 0.15
    x1 = 0.65
    y0 = 0.35
    y1 = 0.8
    x3 = 0.9
    y3 = 0.1
    a = (x0, y0)
    b = (x0, y1)
    c = (x1, y1)
    d = (x1, y0)
    e = (x3, y3)
    img = canvas() do
        for (loc, label) in [(a, "sâ‚"), (b, "sâ‚‚"), (c, "sâ‚ƒ"), (d, "sâ‚„"), (e, "sâ‚…")]
            sq &gt;&gt; loc

<div class="markdown"><p>To map a MIS problem to a tensor network, we first assign degrees of freedom <span class="tex">$s_i,s_j,\ldots s_n \in \&#123;0,1\&#125;$</span> to vertices.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(14cm, 7cm)
    sq = nodestyle(:circle, fill("black"); r=0.02)
    wb = nodestyle(:circle, fill("black"); r=0.06)
    eb = bondstyle(:line)
    tb = textstyle(:default, fontsize(20px), fill("white"))
    tb2 = textstyle(:default, fontsize(20px), fill("black"), font("times"))
    tb3 = textstyle(:default, fontsize(15px), fill("green"))
    x0 = 0.15
    x1 = 0.65
    y0 = 0.35
    y1 = 0.8
    x3 = 0.9
    y3 = 0.1
    a = (x0, y0)
    b = (x0, y1)
    c = (x1, y1)
    d = (x1, y0)
    e = (x3, y3)
    img = canvas() do
        for (loc, label) in [(a, "â†‘"), (b, "â†“"), (c, "â†‘"), (d, "â†‘"), (e, "â†“")]
            sq &gt;&gt; loc
            #tb2 &gt;&gt; (loc, label)
        end
        for (edge, label) in [((a, b), "+1"), ((b, c), "-1"), ((c, d), "-1"), ((a, d), "+1"), ((d,e), "+1"), ((c, a), "+1")]
            eb &gt;&gt; edge
            wb &gt;&gt; ((edge[1] .+ edge[2]) ./ 2)
            tb &gt;&gt; ((edge[1] .+ edge[2]) ./ 2, label == "+1" ? "Tâ‚‘" : "Tâ‚‘'")
        end
        for lt in [((0.08, 0.3),"Táµ¥Â³"), ((0.08,0.75), "Táµ¥Â²"), ((0.75, 0.35),"Táµ¥Â³"), ((0.75,0.8), "Táµ¥Â²"), ((0.97,0.1), "Táµ¥Â¹")]
            tb2 &gt;&gt; lt
        end
        for (i,edge) in enumerate([(a, b), (b, c), (c, d), (a, d), (d,e), (c, a)])
            tb3 &gt;&gt; (edge[1] .* 0.2 .+ edge[2] .* 0.8, "($i, T)")
            tb3 &gt;&gt; (edge[1] .* 0.8 .+ edge[2] .* 0.2, "($i, F)")
        end
    end
    Compose.compose(context(.38, 0, .5, 1), img)
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><p>We can put a bond matrix at the bond to describe the independence restriction</p>
<p class="tex">$$T_&#123;e&#125; &#61; \begin&#123;bmatrix&#125;0 &amp; 0 \\0 &amp; -\infty\end&#123;bmatrix&#125;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function mis_bondtensor(::Type{T}) where T
    res = ones(T, 2, 2)
    res[2, 2] = zero(T)
    return res
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-mis_bondtensor' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>mis_bondtensor (generic function with 1 method)</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>The vertex tensors are for counting the number of vertices</p>
<p class="tex">$$T_&#123;v&#125; &#61; \begin&#123;bmatrix&#125;
0\\
1
\end&#123;bmatrix&#125;$$</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>function mis_vertextensor(::Type{T}) where T
    T[0, 1]
end</code></pre>
<pre id='var-mis_vertextensor' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>mis_vertextensor (generic function with 1 method)</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>We can build a tensor tensor network for solving this issue. The tensor network is contracted with a greedy order.</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>contraction_result_mis = ein"ab,bc,cd,ad,de,ac,a,b,c,d,e-&gt;"(fill(mis_bondtensor(CountingTropical{Float64}), 6)..., fill(mis_vertextensor(CountingTropical{Float64}), 5)...)[]</code></pre>
<pre id='var-contraction_result_mis' class='code-output documenter-example-output'>(2.0, 4.0)â‚œ</pre>


<div class="markdown"><p>There are 4 possible configurations</p>
</div>

    img1 = viz_lattice(SquareLattice(32,32); r=0.01, ncolor=2)

	<td><p>Wall clock time for computing the ground state energy of the &#40;a&#41; Ising spin glass on an open square lattice with <span class="tex">$L^2$</span> spins. &#40;tensor networks are contracted with <a href="https://github.com/QuantumBFS/Yao.jl">Yao.jl</a>&#41;</p>

<div class="markdown"><p><strong>Ising spin glass on cubic lattices</strong></p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(14cm*0.4, 7cm*0.8)
    Î¸ = 2.31
    Ï• = 2.8
    cam_position = SVector(0.0, 0.0, 0.5)
    rot = RotY(Î¸)*RotX(Ï•)
    cam_transform = PerspectiveMap() âˆ˜ inv(AffineMap(rot, rot*cam_position))
    Nx = Ny = Nz = 6
    nb = [nodestyle(:circle, fill(color); r=0.015) for color in ["#CC4040", "#4040CC"]]
    eb = bondstyle(:default, stroke("#333333"), linewidth(0.2mm); r=0.01)
    c = Cubic((0.05, 0.05, 0.05))
    x(i,j,k) = cam_transform(SVector(c[i-Nx/2-0.5,j-Ny/2-0.5,k-Nz/2-0.5])).data
    fig = canvas() do
        for i=1:Nx, j=1:Ny, k=1:Nz
            rand(nb) &gt;&gt; x(i,j,k)
            i!=Nx && eb &gt;&gt; (x(i,j,k), x(i+1,j,k))
            j!=Ny && eb &gt;&gt; (x(i,j,k), x(i,j+1,k))
            k!=Nz && eb &gt;&gt; (x(i,j,k), x(i,j,k+1))
        end
    end
    leftright(Compose.compose(context(0.5,0.5, 1.0, 1.0), fig), md"""Ground state and degeneracy on cubic lattice up to $6^3$ spins. 
""")
end</code></pre>

	<td><p>Ground-state energy, entropy, and computational time of <span class="tex">$q &#61; 3$</span> state Potts spin glass model on square lattices of sizes <span class="tex">$n &#61; 4\sim 18$</span>. Each data point is averaged over <span class="tex">$100$</span> random instances computed on a single GPU. As a comparison, the existing branch-and-cut method with the Semi-Definite Programming energy lower bounds method on the same model works up to <span class="tex">$9 \times 9$</span> lattices &#40;using 10 hours&#41;</p>

<div class="markdown"><p><strong>Ising spin glass and Max-2-SAT on random 3-regular graphs</strong></p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    function rand_3regular_tn(::Type{T}, n; D=2) where T
        g = LightGraphs.random_regular_graph(n, 3)
        labels = 1:ne(g)
        arrays = [rand(T, fill(2, 3)...) for i=1:n]
        labels = [Int[] for i=1:n]
        for (k, e) in enumerate(LightGraphs.edges(g))
            push!(labels[e.src], k)
            push!(labels[e.dst], k)
        end
        tensors = LabeledTensor.(arrays, labels)
        TensorNetwork(tensors)
    end

    img = viz_graph(random_regular_graph(220, 3), linecolor="black", node_fontsize=0)
    #leftright(img, updown(html"""&lt;img src="https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6257240/109566350-bb977f00-7ab1-11eb-953f-127d7919e3e6.png" width=270px/&gt;""", md"Wall clock time for computing the ground state energy of Ising spin glass on the chimera graph with the ``L \times L`` unit cell (``8L^2`` spins)."))
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(7cm, 6cm)
    leftright(Compose.compose(context(0.0, 0.0, 6/7, 1.0), img), md"""
The spin glass on the random graphs: our method can compute optimal solutions and count the number of solutions for spin glasses and combinatorial optimization problems on on $3$ regular random graphs up to $220$ spins, on a single GPU. This is inaccessible by existing methods.
""")
end</code></pre>

	<td><p>The spin glass on the random graphs: our method can compute optimal solutions and count the number of solutions for spin glasses and combinatorial optimization problems on on <span class="tex">$3$</span> regular random graphs up to <span class="tex">$220$</span> spins, on a single GPU. This is inaccessible by existing methods.</p>

<div class="markdown"><h2>The Song Shan Lake Spring School &#40;SSSS&#41; Challenge</h2>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>In 2019, Lei Wang, Pan Zhang, Roger and me released a challenge in the Song Shan Lake Spring School, the one gives the largest number of solutions to the challenge quiz can take a macbook home &#40;<a href="https://github.com/LinuxDaFaHao">@LinuxDaFaHao</a>&#41;. Students submitted more than 10 <a href="https://github.com/QuantumBFS/SSSS/blob/master/Challenge.md">solutions to the problem</a>. The quiz is</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>let
    Î¸2 = 0.5
    Ï•2 = 0.8
    Compose.set_default_graphic_size(12cm, 12cm)
    cam_position = SVector(0.0, 0.0, 0.5)
    rot = RotY(Î¸2)*RotX(Ï•2)
    cam_transform = PerspectiveMap() âˆ˜ inv(AffineMap(rot, rot*cam_position))
    Nx = Ny = Nz = 4
    nb = nodestyle(:circle; r=0.01)
    eb = bondstyle(:default; r=0.01)
    x(i,j,k) = cam_transform(SVector(i,j,k) .* 0.03).data
    fl = fullerene()
    fig = canvas() do
        for (i,j,k) in fl
            nb &gt;&gt; x(i,j,k)
            for (i2,j2,k2) in fl
                (i2-i)^2+(j2-j)^2+(k2-k)^2 &lt; 5.0 && eb &gt;&gt; (x(i,j,k), x(i2,j2,k2))
            end
        end
    end
    Compose.compose(context(0.5,0.5, 1.0, 1.0), fig)
end</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><p>In the Buckyball structure as shown in the figure, we attach an ising spin <span class="tex">$s_i&#61;\pm 1$</span> on each vertex. The neighboring spins interact with an anti-ferromagnetic coupling of unit strength.</p>
<ol>
<li><p>Get <span class="tex">$\ln Z/N$</span>, where <span class="tex">$N$</span> is the number of vertices, and</p>
</li>
</ol>
<p class="tex">$$Z &#61; \sum_&#123;\&#123;s\&#125;&#125;e^&#123;-\sum_&#123;i,j \in E&#125;s_i s_j&#125;$$</p>
<ol start="2">
<li><p>Count the ground state degeneracy.</p>
</li>
</ol>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><p>Now we are proud to announce a new solution to this quiz</p>
</div>

<pre class='language-julia'><code class='language-julia'>c60_contraction_masks = let
    function contraction_mask(ne::SlicedEinsum)
        contraction_mask!(ne.eins, [zeros(Bool, length(getixsv(ne)))])
    end
    # compute the vertex elimination order
    function contraction_mask!(ne::NestedEinsum, results)
        if OMEinsum.isleaf(ne)
        else
            for arg in ne.args
                contraction_mask!(arg, results)
            end
            eliminated_vertices = setdiff(âˆª(getixsv(ne.eins)...), getiyv(ne.eins))
            mask = copy(results[end])
            mask[eliminated_vertices] .= true
            push!(results, mask)
        end
        return results
    end
    contraction_mask(c60_code)
end;</code></pre>

<div class="markdown"><p>Since the complexity of tensor contraction is exponential to the number of legs involved, <em>&quot;what is the optimal contraction order&quot;</em> becomes one of the most important issues in tensor network contraction. The greedy algorithm we used here is efficient but not optimal. Finding the optimal contraction order itself is NP-hard.</p>
</div>


<div class="markdown"><h2>Towards productivity</h2>
<p>To solve large scale problems. You also need a good contraction order algorithm, e.g.</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Finding the optimal contracting order for <code>einsum</code>, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2005.06787">Classical Simulation of Quantum Supremacy Circuits</a>.</p>
</li>
<li><p>A heuristic algorithm for contraction order <a href="https://journals.aps.org/prl/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevLett.125.060503">Contracting Arbitrary Tensor Networks: General Approximate Algorithm and Applications in Graphical Models and Quantum Circuit Simulations</a></p>
</li>
<li><p>For simple lattices, you can also map the problem to <a href="https://github.com/QuantumBFS/Yao.jl">Yao.jl</a> for fast contraction.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>The Tropical BLAS project is under the progress,</p>
<ul>
<li><p>Tropical GEMM on CPU for Tropical numbers &#40;<a href="https://github.com/TensorBFS/TropicalGEMM.jl">DONE</a>&#41;,</p>
</li>
<li><p>Tropical GEMM on GPU &#40;WIP&#41;,</p>
</li>
<li><p>Tropical GEMM for CountingTropical numbers,</p>
</li>
</ul>
</div>
